  {id:119,name:"AI Training Data Workers (Global South Ghost Workers)",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Workers in Kenya, Colombia, Uganda paid $2-3/hour to label traumatic content — the invisible labor behind AI.",
   description:"Every major AI model depends on an army of invisible workers — primarily in Kenya, Uganda, Colombia, Philippines, and Venezuela — paid $1-3/hour to label data, moderate disturbing content, and provide the human feedback that makes AI seem intelligent. TIME Magazine's 2023 investigation revealed Kenyan Sama workers labeling torture, child abuse, and beheadings for OpenAI at $2/hour. These workers have no labor protections, no psychological support, and are contractually silenced.",
   whyNow:"TIME's expose and follow-on investigations have created public awareness. The EU AI Act requires supply chain transparency for high-risk AI. Kenyan worker unions are organizing. The contrast between AI executive pay and ghost worker pay is becoming a class-struggle narrative.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"DAIR Institute",url:"https://www.dair-institute.org"},{name:"AI Now Institute",url:"https://ainowinstitute.org"},{name:"Data Workers Inquiry",url:"https://data-workers.org"},{name:"Foxglove Legal",url:"https://www.foxglove.org.uk"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"EU AI Act supply chain provisions. ILO digital work recommendations. Kenya Employment Act amendments pending.",
   sources:[{title:"TIME — OpenAI's Kenyan Workers",url:"https://time.com/6247678/openai-chatgpt-kenya-workers/"},{title:"MIT Technology Review — AI Ghost Work",url:"https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/04/28/1072106/the-workers-behind-ai-rarely-see-its-rewards/"},{title:"DAIR Institute Research",url:"https://www.dair-institute.org/research"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:6,conformity_trap_risk:5,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:5,broad_angle_potential:6,leader_persistence:6,overall_readiness:36},
   intervention_levers:"Labor rights framing connects to gig economy movement. Supply chain transparency requirements.",deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",slogans:["#GhostWorkers","Pay AI workers fairly","The humans behind the machine"]},

  {id:122,name:"AI Energy & Water Crisis — Data Centers",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"AI data centers doubling electricity demand and consuming billions of gallons of water in drought-stricken communities.",
   description:"IEA projects data center electricity demand will double by 2026, with AI workloads the primary driver. Microsoft's water usage increased 34% in one year — 1.7 billion gallons — primarily for cooling data centers. Amazon, Google, and Microsoft are building massive campuses in drought-stricken Arizona, New Mexico, and Virginia, competing with agriculture and municipal water supplies. Nuclear plants are being reopened and coal plants kept online specifically to power data centers.",
   whyNow:"Drought conditions in the American West are at historic levels. Multiple communities are suing over water rights. Arizona passed temporary data center water moratoriums. The IEA spring 2026 report will quantify the scale. This is the window before the buildout becomes irreversible.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Sierra Club — Beyond Dirty Energy",url:"https://www.sierraclub.org/policy/energy/coal"},{name:"AI Now Institute",url:"https://ainowinstitute.org"},{name:"Environmental Defense Fund",url:"https://www.edf.org"},{name:"Water Defense",url:"https://www.waterdefense.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Arizona data center water moratorium (2024). EPA water quality reviews. State-level AI energy disclosure bills moving in CA, NY, WA.",
   sources:[{title:"IEA — Data Centres and Data Transmission Networks",url:"https://www.iea.org/energy-system/buildings/data-centres-and-data-transmission-networks"},{title:"Washington Post — AI Water Consumption",url:"https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/09/09/microsoft-ai-water-usage/"},{title:"NRDC — Data Centers & Energy",url:"https://www.nrdc.org/resources/data-center-efficiency-assessment"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:8,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:9,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:45},
   intervention_levers:"Environmental justice framing connects AI expansion to local water scarcity. Regulatory windows in drought-affected states.",deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",slogans:["#AIWaterCrisis","Water > Data Centers","Cool the servers not the planet"]},

  {id:124,name:"Meta Teen Mental Health — Big Tobacco Moment",region:"United States",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Meta knowingly harmed teenage girls and suppressed internal research — the same playbook as Big Tobacco.",
   description:"Internal Facebook/Instagram documents — leaked by Frances Haugen in 2021 and now entering federal court discovery — prove Meta knew Instagram worsened body image, depression, and suicidal ideation in teenage girls. 42+ state AGs have filed suit. The MDL (Multi-District Litigation) consolidating hundreds of cases has 2026 trial dates. The analogy to 1990s tobacco litigation is precise: the industry knew, suppressed findings, and kept marketing to minors.",
   whyNow:"MDL trial dates in 2026 will force internal documents into public record. Surgeon General Vivek Murthy issued a formal advisory calling social media a public health crisis. The Kids Online Safety Act has bipartisan support. This is the deposition phase — the moment before the dam breaks.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Center for Humane Technology",url:"https://www.humanetech.com"},{name:"Fairplay for Kids",url:"https://fairplayforkids.org"},{name:"Common Sense Media",url:"https://www.commonsensemedia.org"},{name:"State AG coalition",url:"https://naag.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Kids Online Safety Act (KOSA) Senate passage 2024. COPPA 2.0 pending. MDL trial dates 2026. FTC investigation ongoing.",
   sources:[{title:"WSJ — The Facebook Files",url:"https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-facebook-files-11631713039"},{title:"Surgeon General Advisory on Social Media",url:"https://www.hhs.gov/surgeongeneral/priorities/youth-mental-health/social-media/index.html"},{title:"Center for Humane Technology",url:"https://www.humanetech.com/youth"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:9,conformity_trap_risk:8,benefit_visibility:9,penalty_reduction:8,broad_angle_potential:9,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:51},
   intervention_levers:"State AG coalition provides litigation infrastructure. Internal documents (à la tobacco) create accountability narrative.",deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",slogans:["#ProtectKidsOnline","Meta knew","Social media is not safe for kids"]},

  {id:142,name:"France Far-Right Municipal Conquest",region:"France",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Rassemblement National achieving best-ever municipal election results, normalizing far-right governance at local level.",
   description:"The Rassemblement National's March 15-22, 2026 municipal election results mark a qualitative shift — from parliamentary opposition to actual governing power in hundreds of French cities. Once in power, RN mayors have restricted cultural funding, limited civil society access, and changed local policing priorities. The pattern mirrors how the far right consolidated power in Italy and Hungary: local government first, then national.",
   whyNow:"RN is governing rather than just opposing. The cultural and institutional changes at municipal level are happening now — libraries, cultural centers, anti-discrimination offices being defunded. The window to document and resist is open before these become permanent governance norms.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"La France Insoumise",url:"https://lafranceinsoumise.fr"},{name:"SOS Racisme",url:"https://www.sos-racisme.org"},{name:"LICRA",url:"https://www.licra.org"},{name:"Observatoire des municipalités RN",url:""}],
   regulatoryWindow:"French constitutional provisions on municipal governance. EU Rule of Law framework. Council of Europe ECHR oversight.",
   sources:[{title:"Le Monde — Résultats Municipales 2026",url:"https://www.lemonde.fr/politique/"},{title:"Fondation Jean-Jaurès — Rapport RN Municipal",url:"https://www.jean-jaures.org"},{title:"Libération — RN au pouvoir local",url:"https://www.liberation.fr"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:9,conformity_trap_risk:8,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:47},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",slogans:["#RésistanceLocale","La démocratie se défend","Non au RN"]},

  {id:143,name:"Marine Le Pen Appeal — Democracy on Trial",region:"France",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"49% of French voters support a party whose leader may be legally barred from elections for embezzlement.",
   description:"Marine Le Pen's July 7, 2026 appeal against her 5-year election ban (for embezzling €4.4M of EU funds) creates a constitutional moment: if upheld, the most popular politician in France is barred from the 2027 presidential election. If overturned, it signals that laws don't apply to populist leaders. RN has already framed any conviction as judicial persecution — making this a test of rule-of-law norms under democratic pressure.",
   whyNow:"The appeal verdict date (July 7, 2026) is 9 months before the 2027 presidential election. However the court rules, the result will either galvanize or deflate democratic norms. Civil society needs to be organized with clear messaging frameworks in advance.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Transparency International France",url:"https://www.transparency-france.org"},{name:"Anticor",url:"https://www.anticor.org"},{name:"ATTAC France",url:"https://www.france.attac.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Court of Appeal verdict July 7, 2026. Potential ECHR challenge. 2027 presidential election calendar.",
   sources:[{title:"France 24 — Le Pen Trial Timeline",url:"https://www.france24.com/en/europe/20240323-le-pen-faces-parliamentary-expenses-fraud-trial"},{title:"Euronews — French Democracy",url:"https://www.euronews.com/my-europe/2026/03/03/france"},{title:"Transparency International — Fraud Case",url:"https://www.transparency.org/en/news"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:8,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:5,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:42},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",slogans:["#DémocratieSousCondition","Personne n'est au-dessus de la loi","Justice pour tous"]},

  {id:144,name:"France Anti-Police Violence / Nahel Trial",region:"France",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"The Nahel Merzouk murder trial — point-blank shooting of 17-year-old by police — becomes France's racial justice moment.",
   description:"Officer Florian M.'s murder trial for the point-blank shooting of 17-year-old Nahel Merzouk (June 27, 2023) — captured on video, indisputable — is France's George Floyd moment. The 2023 riots brought 45,000 police, 3,000+ arrested. The trial in mid-2026 will either affirm or deny accountability. France's system of qualified immunity for police (the IGPN 'police des polices') is structurally similar to the pre-2020 US system.",
   whyNow:"The trial date creates a defined accountability moment. ECHR has ongoing proceedings. French law reform on police use of force is actively debated in the National Assembly. The BLM playbook — video evidence, demand for systemic accountability — directly applies.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Justice pour Nahel",url:""},{name:"SOS Racisme",url:"https://www.sos-racisme.org"},{name:"Amnesty International France",url:"https://www.amnesty.fr"},{name:"Ligue des droits de l'homme",url:"https://www.ldh-france.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Criminal trial mid-2026. ECHR proceedings. French National Assembly police reform bills.",
   sources:[{title:"Le Monde — Procès Nahel Merzouk",url:"https://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/"},{title:"Amnesty France — Violences policières",url:"https://www.amnesty.fr/liberte-d-expression/actualites/violences-policieres-en-france"},{title:"Human Rights Watch — France Police",url:"https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2024/country-chapters/france"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:5,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:41},
   intervention_levers:"Coalition between racial justice and police accountability movements. ECHR ruling provides international pressure.",deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",slogans:["#JusticePourNahel","Vérité et justice","Violences policières = crime d'État"]},

  // ===== NEW EMERGING TRENDS (ids 145+) =====

  {id:145,name:"AI Surveillance Expansion — Schools, Workplaces, Public Space",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Facial recognition and AI monitoring expanding beyond law enforcement into schools, workplaces, and public spaces with minimal legal oversight.",
   description:"What started with police body cameras has become ubiquitous surveillance: Clearview AI in schools, Amazon Rekognition in warehouses, China-built cameras in western cities, emotion-detection software in job interviews. 109 US cities and the entire EU have banned or restricted facial recognition in public spaces — but the corporate sector remains largely unregulated. Workers can be fired based on emotion-detection scores. Students are profiled before they commit any act. Facial recognition errors run 10-100x higher for Black and brown faces.",
   whyNow:"The EU AI Act begins enforcing biometric surveillance bans in public spaces from August 2026. US federal legislation is stalled but 15+ states have active bills. The 'school-to-prison pipeline' framing connects this to racial justice movements. Amazon and Microsoft face shareholder resolutions on facial recognition.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Algorithmic Justice League",url:"https://www.ajl.org"},{name:"Electronic Frontier Foundation",url:"https://www.eff.org/issues/facial-recognition"},{name:"ACLU — Surveillance",url:"https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/surveillance-by-schools"},{name:"Fight for the Future",url:"https://www.banfacialrecognition.com"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"EU AI Act biometric surveillance ban August 2026. US federal Facial Recognition and Biometric Technology Moratorium Act. State BIPA-style laws in 15+ states.",
   sources:[{title:"ACLU — Face Surveillance",url:"https://www.aclu.org/news/privacy-technology/america-cant-ban-face-surveillance-in-schools"},{title:"Algorithmic Justice League",url:"https://www.ajl.org"},{title:"Fight for the Future — Ban Facial Recognition",url:"https://www.banfacialrecognition.com"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:42},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#BanFacialRecognition","My face is not your data","Surveillance is not safety"]},

  {id:146,name:"Platform Power / EU Digital Services Act Enforcement",region:"Europe/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"EU forcing Big Tech to actually moderate harmful content and open algorithms — first major test of platform accountability law.",
   description:"The EU Digital Services Act (DSA) is in full enforcement as of 2024, requiring very large platforms to audit algorithms, remove illegal content, and provide researcher data access. The European Commission has launched formal investigations against X (Twitter), TikTok, Meta, and YouTube. TikTok faces €1.8B fines. X/Twitter has been designated a non-compliant VLOP (Very Large Online Platform). This is the first real test of whether democracies can hold platforms accountable.",
   whyNow:"The Commission's 2026 enforcement actions are reaching fine-and-compliance phase. TikTok ban debates in US and EU are converging. Meta's algorithm transparency lawsuit in the US federal courts has a 2026 hearing. The DSA creates a precedent that other jurisdictions are watching to replicate.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"European Commission — DG CONNECT",url:"https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/digital-services-act-package"},{name:"EDRi (European Digital Rights)",url:"https://edri.org"},{name:"Mozilla Foundation",url:"https://foundation.mozilla.org"},{name:"AlgorithmWatch",url:"https://algorithmwatch.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"DSA full enforcement ongoing. EC investigations against X, TikTok, Meta in progress. US platform liability reform debates.",
   sources:[{title:"European Commission — DSA Enforcement",url:"https://commission.europa.eu/strategy-and-policy/priorities-2019-2024/europe-fit-digital-age/digital-services-act_en"},{title:"AlgorithmWatch — DSA Tracker",url:"https://algorithmwatch.org/en/dsa-tracker/"},{title:"EDRi — Platform Accountability",url:"https://edri.org/our-work/platformaccountability/"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:42},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#DigitalServicesAct","Algorithms are not neutral","Make platforms accountable"]},

  {id:147,name:"AI Worker Displacement — Hollywood, Warehouses, White Collar",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"AI automation eliminating jobs faster than new ones are created, with no social safety net or transition support.",
   description:"The SAG-AFTRA and WGA strikes of 2023 won contractual AI protections — the first labor agreements explicitly governing AI use. UPS and Amazon are deploying warehouse automation at scale, reducing headcount by 30-40%. McKinsey projects 400 million jobs globally at high automation risk by 2030. White-collar workers in law, accounting, and journalism are seeing AI replace entry-level positions. The Hollywood precedent is the playbook for every sector.",
   whyNow:"The Hollywood contracts expire in 2026, creating a renegotiation window. Amazon's warehouse automation expansion is happening now. Multiple countries (UK, Germany, France) have active AI-and-labor policy processes. The UAW, Teamsters, and SEIU are building AI task forces. This is the formation window for labor's AI response.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"SAG-AFTRA",url:"https://www.sagaftra.org"},{name:"WGA — Writers Guild",url:"https://www.wga.org"},{name:"AFL-CIO Technology Institute",url:"https://www.aflcio.org/technology"},{name:"Warehouse Workers for Justice",url:"https://www.warehouseworker.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"SAG-AFTRA contract renegotiation 2026. EU AI Act high-risk employment applications August 2026. US AI Accountability Act pending.",
   sources:[{title:"SAG-AFTRA AI Agreement",url:"https://www.sagaftra.org/sag-aftra-reaches-tentative-agreement-ai"},{title:"WGA — AI and Writing",url:"https://www.wga.org/the-guild/about-the-guild/artificial-intelligence"},{title:"AFL-CIO — Workers and AI",url:"https://www.aflcio.org/technology/workers-and-artificial-intelligence"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:42},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#AINotOurReplacement","Writers are not prompts","Automate profits share the gains"]},

  {id:148,name:"Climate Attribution Lawsuits — Cities vs. Fossil Fuel Companies",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Cities and states suing fossil fuel majors for billions in climate damages — following the tobacco litigation model.",
   description:"Over 30 US cities and states — including New York, Chicago, Honolulu, and California — have filed suit against ExxonMobil, Shell, BP, and Chevron, alleging the companies knew about climate change since the 1970s, funded denial, and caused specific, calculable damages. The cases are out of the dismissal phase and entering discovery. Internal Exxon documents, already obtained, show projections of sea level rise as far back as 1982. The Big Tobacco parallel is exact: industry knew, suppressed, and marketed aggressively.",
   whyNow:"Courts have cleared the way for discovery — the deposition phase begins in 2025-2026. Internal documents will become public record. Hawaii's case has a 2025 trial date. The IPCC attribution science now makes it possible to quantify specific damages caused by specific emissions. This is the window before settlements or verdicts.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Earthjustice",url:"https://earthjustice.org"},{name:"ClientEarth",url:"https://www.clientearth.org"},{name:"Center for Climate Integrity",url:"https://climateintegrity.org"},{name:"Our Children's Trust",url:"https://www.ourchildrenstrust.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Hawaii case trial 2025. NYC, California, and Colorado cases entering discovery 2026. EU corporate sustainability due diligence directive.",
   sources:[{title:"Center for Climate Integrity — Litigation Tracker",url:"https://climateintegrity.org/climate-litigation"},{title:"Columbia Law — Climate Litigation Database",url:"https://climatecasechart.com"},{title:"The Guardian — Fossil Fuel Lawsuits",url:"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-litigation"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:43},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#FossilFuelAccountability","They knew","Make polluters pay"]},

  {id:149,name:"Youth Mental Health / Social Media Platform Liability",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Social media platforms designed to addict children facing a wave of state legislation, federal suits, and a Surgeon General advisory — a paradigm shift in platform liability.",
   description:"The US Surgeon General issued an unprecedented advisory calling social media a public health crisis for youth (2023). 42+ state AGs sued Meta. The Kids Online Safety Act passed the Senate 91-3 in 2024. Australia banned social media for under-16s. Florida banned it for under-14s. The MDL against Meta, TikTok, Snap, and YouTube consolidates 1,000+ lawsuits alleging the platforms knowingly designed addictive features targeting children. Internal documents proving Meta's knowledge are now in discovery.",
   whyNow:"MDL trial dates in 2026 will force documents into public view. Australia's ban (Nov 2024) demonstrated political feasibility. The Surgeon General's push for warning labels has bipartisan support in Congress. Several states have passed age verification laws already being enforced.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Center for Humane Technology",url:"https://www.humanetech.com/youth"},{name:"Fairplay for Kids",url:"https://fairplayforkids.org"},{name:"Common Sense Media",url:"https://www.commonsensemedia.org/research/the-common-sense-census-media-use-by-tweens-and-teens"},{name:"ParentsTogether",url:"https://parents-together.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Kids Online Safety Act pending House vote. MDL 2026 trial dates. Australia's ban precedent. EU Digital Services Act under-18 protections.",
   sources:[{title:"Surgeon General Advisory — Social Media",url:"https://www.hhs.gov/surgeongeneral/priorities/youth-mental-health/social-media/index.html"},{title:"KOSA — Senate Vote",url:"https://www.congress.gov/bill/118th-congress/senate-bill/1409"},{title:"Center for Humane Technology — Youth",url:"https://www.humanetech.com/youth"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:8,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:9,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:9,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:48},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#ProtectKidsOnline","Social media is not safe for kids","Warn parents now"]},

  {id:150,name:"Anti-SLAPP / Press Freedom & Journalist Surveillance",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Corporations and governments using litigation and surveillance to silence journalists and whistleblowers — a direct attack on the information commons.",
   description:"Strategic Lawsuits Against Public Participation (SLAPPs) have become a primary tool to silence investigative journalists: Giuliani v. Georgia election workers, billionaires suing reporters, and the $1.3B Dominion-Fox settlement normalized weaponizing defamation law. Simultaneously, the NSO Group Pegasus spyware infected phones of 50+ journalists, and the US prosecuted more whistleblowers under the Espionage Act than all prior administrations combined. A federal anti-SLAPP law has been proposed but not passed.",
   whyNow:"The Pegasus Project documentation (2021-2024) has created an evidentiary record. The European Anti-SLAPP Directive was adopted in 2024. Whistleblower prosecutions are escalating under the current US administration. The Freedom of the Press Foundation tracks an accelerating pattern.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Freedom of the Press Foundation",url:"https://freedom.press"},{name:"Committee to Protect Journalists",url:"https://cpj.org"},{name:"Reporters Without Borders",url:"https://rsf.org"},{name:"Electronic Frontier Foundation",url:"https://www.eff.org/issues/bloggers/legal/threat/slapp"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"EU Anti-SLAPP Directive 2024. US SPEAK FREE Act pending. Shield law debates in Congress.",
   sources:[{title:"Freedom of the Press Foundation",url:"https://freedom.press"},{title:"RSF — Press Freedom Index 2025",url:"https://rsf.org/en/index"},{title:"CPJ — Journalist Protection",url:"https://cpj.org/safety/"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:6,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:5,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:38},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#ProtectJournalists","SLAPP suits silence truth","A free press is not optional"]},

  {id:151,name:"Extreme Weather Insurance Collapse — Florida & California",region:"United States",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Private insurance markets collapsing in climate-vulnerable states as actuaries price in reality that politicians deny.",
   description:"State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, and 7 other major insurers have withdrawn from California and/or Florida entirely. 1.2 million Florida homeowners are now on the state's 'insurer of last resort' (Citizens). Average California home insurance has risen 300% in high-risk areas. This is the market acknowledging what politicians deny: climate change makes coastal and wildfire-prone property uninsurable at current prices. The insurance collapse is a direct feedback loop from climate inaction — and the first loss that middle-class homeowners feel in their wallets.",
   whyNow:"FEMA's flood map revision (2026) will reclassify millions of properties as high-risk, triggering mandatory flood insurance requirements and mortgage denials. California's FAIR Plan is approaching insolvency. This creates a middle-class constituency for climate action who've never cared before.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Environmental Defense Fund",url:"https://www.edf.org"},{name:"Natural Resources Defense Council",url:"https://www.nrdc.org"},{name:"First Street Foundation",url:"https://firststreet.org"},{name:"Center for American Progress",url:"https://www.americanprogress.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"FEMA flood map revision 2026. California Department of Insurance emergency rulemaking. Congress flood insurance program reauthorization.",
   sources:[{title:"First Street Foundation — Climate Risk",url:"https://firststreet.org/research-library/"},{title:"NYT — Insurance Companies Leave California",url:"https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/01/business/state-farm-california-home-insurance.html"},{title:"ProPublica — Florida Insurance Crisis",url:"https://www.propublica.org/series/climate-insurance"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:8,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:9,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:45},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#ClimateInsurance","When the market prices in reality","Uninsurable = uninhabitable"]},

  {id:152,name:"Deep Sea Mining Moratorium Battle",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Extractive industry racing to mine Pacific seafloor for EV battery minerals before international regulations finalized.",
   description:"The International Seabed Authority (ISA) is under pressure from mining companies (led by The Metals Company/DeepGreen backed by Canada's TMC) to issue the first deep-sea mining licenses in the Clarion-Clipperton Zone of the Pacific — 10 million km² of largely unexplored seafloor. 21 countries including France, Germany, Chile, and Pacific Island nations have called for a moratorium. Scientists warn that sediment plumes from mining could disrupt oxygen cycles across the Pacific. The ISA's own legal counsel says regulations aren't ready.",
   whyNow:"The ISA Council meeting in 2026 is the critical governance moment. Norway approved licenses in its EEZ in 2024 against international protest. COP31 in Australia creates a compound pressure point. Pacific Island nations — already fighting climate change — have existential stakes.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Deep Sea Conservation Coalition",url:"https://www.savethehighseas.org"},{name:"Pacific Community (SPC)",url:"https://www.spc.int"},{name:"Fauna & Flora International",url:"https://www.fauna-flora.org"},{name:"International Union for Conservation of Nature",url:"https://www.iucn.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"ISA Council 2026 meeting. COP31 Australia November 2026. High Seas Treaty ratification ongoing.",
   sources:[{title:"Deep Sea Conservation Coalition",url:"https://www.savethehighseas.org/deep-sea-mining/"},{title:"Nature — Deep Sea Mining Science",url:"https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-021-01400-3"},{title:"Pacific Community — DSM Position",url:"https://www.spc.int/updates/news/press-releases/2021/06/pacific-community-reaffirms-support-for-deep-sea-mining-moratorium"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:41},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#ProtectTheDeepSea","The deep ocean is not a mine","Moratorium now"]},

  {id:153,name:"PFAS Forever Chemicals — Contamination & Accountability",region:"United States/Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"97% of Americans have PFAS in their blood; EPA just set near-zero limits; industry fighting back while contamination is irreversible.",
   description:"Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) — 'forever chemicals' used in non-stick cookware, food packaging, firefighting foam, and hundreds of industrial applications — have contaminated virtually every water supply in the US. The EPA set maximum contamination limits for 6 PFAS at near-zero levels in April 2024, triggering massive compliance costs and industry lawsuits. 3M settled for $10.3 billion. DuPont settled for $1.18 billion. But the contamination is permanent — PFAS don't break down in the environment or human bodies.",
   whyNow:"The EPA MCL (Maximum Contaminant Level) rule took effect 2024 — water utilities must comply by 2027. 3M and DuPont settlements create accountability precedent. Congressional Republicans are attempting to roll back the EPA rules. The health equity angle (communities of color near military bases have highest exposure) is underreported.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Environmental Working Group",url:"https://www.ewg.org/tapwater/pfas"},{name:"PEER — Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility",url:"https://www.peer.org"},{name:"Environmental Defense Fund",url:"https://www.edf.org"},{name:"Earthjustice",url:"https://earthjustice.org/issues/chemical-safety"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"EPA PFAS MCL compliance deadline 2027. DOD PFAS cleanup mandate. Congressional rollback attempts 2026.",
   sources:[{title:"EPA — PFAS National Primary Drinking Water Regulation",url:"https://www.epa.gov/sdwa/and-polyfluoroalkyl-substances-pfas"},{title:"EWG — PFAS Contamination Map",url:"https://www.ewg.org/research/national-pfas-testing/"},{title:"Environmental Health News",url:"https://www.ehn.org/pfas-contamination"}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:8,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:45},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#BanPFAS","Forever chemicals forever problem","Clean water is a right"]},

  // ===== UN GLOBAL CASES 2026 (IDs 200-211) =====

  {id:200,name:"Global Plastics Treaty (INC-5.4 Negotiations)",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Plastic Pollution",
   description:"The UN Intergovernmental Negotiating Committee (INC) is working toward a legally binding global plastics treaty covering the full plastic lifecycle. After stalled negotiations at INC-5.1 (Busan, Nov 2024) and INC-5.2 (Geneva, Aug 2025) and the resignation of the chair, a new chair (Julio Cordano of Chile) was elected at the procedural INC-5.3 session on Feb 7, 2026. Substantive negotiations expected at INC-5.4 (date/location TBD, mid-2026).",
   whyNow:"Negotiations are at a critical inflection point: a new chair has been elected after months of obstruction. Civil society pushing for a reset with an ambitious, legally binding treaty that addresses plastic production, not just waste. The INC-5.4 session is the next major make-or-break moment before the process loses all momentum.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Center for International Environmental Law (CIEL)",url:"https://www.ciel.org"},{name:"UNEP INC Secretariat",url:"https://www.unep.org/inc-plastic-pollution"},{name:"Break Free From Plastic",url:"https://www.breakfreefromplastic.org"},{name:"High Ambition Coalition to End Plastic Pollution",url:"https://hactoendplasticpollution.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"INC-5.4 (mid-2026, TBD) is the next formal negotiation session. Window for civil society pressure is open NOW ahead of scheduling and text finalization.",
   sources:[{title:"CIEL — INC-5.3 Reaction",url:"https://www.ciel.org/news/inc-5-3-reaction/",verified:true},{title:"UNEP INC Plastic Pollution Hub",url:"https://www.unep.org/inc-plastic-pollution",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:4,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:9,leader_persistence:6,overall_readiness:41},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#EndPlasticPollution","#TurnOffTheTap","Break Free From Plastic","#PlasticsTreaty"],tags:["treaty-path","compound-crisis"]},

  {id:201,name:"BBNJ High Seas Treaty — First COP",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Ocean Governance / Biodiversity",
   description:"The UN High Seas Treaty (BBNJ Agreement — Biodiversity Beyond National Jurisdiction) entered into force on January 17, 2026, after 60 countries ratified. It creates the first legal framework to protect marine biodiversity in international waters covering ~50% of Earth's surface. The first Conference of Parties (COP1) must be held within one year of entry into force.",
   whyNow:"COP1 will set the rules for marine protected areas, environmental impact assessments, and benefit-sharing of marine genetic resources for decades. Civil society has a narrow window to shape implementation mechanisms. The 30x30 ocean protection target requires urgent designation of high seas MPAs starting now.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"High Seas Alliance",url:"https://highseasalliance.org"},{name:"Ocean Conservancy",url:"https://oceanconservancy.org"},{name:"World Resources Institute — Oceans",url:"https://www.wri.org/insights/high-seas-treaty-explainer"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"PrepCom 3 (March 23–April 2, 2026) and COP1 (by Jan 2027) are key institutional windows. MPA nominations and benefit-sharing rules being written NOW.",
   sources:[{title:"High Seas Alliance — Treaty Enters Into Force",url:"https://highseasalliance.org/2026/01/16/historic-high-seas-treaty-enters-into-force-launching-a-new-era-of-global-ocean-governance/",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:6,conformity_trap_risk:5,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:39},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#HighSeasTreaty","#30x30","#ProtectTheHighSeas"],tags:["treaty-path","biodiversity"]},

  {id:202,name:"COP31 — Climate Justice & Fossil Fuel Phase-Out",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Climate Change",
   description:"The 31st UN Climate Conference (COP31) will be hosted November 9–20, 2026, with Australia as President of Negotiations and a Pacific pre-COP co-hosted by Australia and Pacific island nations. This COP is the first major climate check-in after the 2025 Global Stocktake, and is expected to pressure countries to update their NDCs for 2035 targets.",
   whyNow:"Australia's presidency creates tension: a coal-exporting nation leading climate negotiations. Civil society mobilizing to demand Australia prove climate leadership through domestic fossil fuel phase-out. Pacific islands provide high emotional stakes. Loss and Damage Fund, NDC ambition, and fossil fuel non-proliferation treaty are key pressure points.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"WWF Australia",url:"https://wwf.org.au/what-we-do/climate/cop31-australias-opportunity/"},{name:"Australian Youth Climate Coalition (AYCC)",url:"https://www.aycc.org.au"},{name:"350.org Pacific",url:"https://350.org"},{name:"Pacific Climate Warriors",url:"https://www.pacificclimatewarriors.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"NDC 2035 targets due by COP31. Loss and Damage Fund capitalization, $1.3 trillion climate finance goal under NCQG are active negotiation items.",
   sources:[{title:"WWF Australia — COP31",url:"https://wwf.org.au/what-we-do/climate/cop31-australias-opportunity/",verified:true},{title:"UNFCCC — Road to COP31",url:"https://unfccc.int/cop31/the-road-to-antalya",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:8,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:9,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:45},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#COP31","#FossilFuelPhaseOut","#LossAndDamage","#PacificsCOP","#ClimateJustice"],tags:["treaty-path","climate"]},

  {id:203,name:"Loss and Damage Fund — Civil Society Mobilization",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Climate Finance / Climate Justice",
   description:"The Fund for Responding to Loss and Damage (FRLD), established at COP27 and operationalized at COP28, is the world's first dedicated mechanism to compensate developing nations for climate harms they did not cause. Civil society is demanding at least $400 billion/year in disbursements through the FRLD, and $724 billion in new grants under the New Collective Quantified Goal (NCQG) by 2030.",
   whyNow:"The FRLD Board is operationalizing direct access, governance, and eligibility rules right now in 2026. Early Board decisions will determine whether the fund reaches frontline communities or gets captured by multilateral bureaucracy. The Loss and Damage Youth Coalition (900+ members, 70+ countries) is a rising mobilization force.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Loss and Damage Collaboration",url:"https://www.lossanddamagecollaboration.org"},{name:"Loss and Damage Youth Coalition",url:"https://ldyouth.org"},{name:"Climate Action Network International",url:"https://climatenetwork.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"FRLD Board sessions in 2026 are setting direct access rules and first disbursement mechanisms. COP31 (Nov 2026) is the next major capitalization pressure point.",
   sources:[{title:"Loss and Damage Collaboration — Finance Project",url:"https://www.lossanddamagecollaboration.org/loss-and-damage-finance-project",verified:true},{title:"FRLD Board — Official",url:"https://www.frld.org/board",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:5,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:8,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:43},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#LossAndDamage","#PayUpForClimateJustice","#ClimateJustice"],tags:["climate-finance","global-south"]},

  {id:204,name:"WHO Pandemic Accord — Ratification & Implementation",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Global Health / Health Equity",
   description:"The WHO Pandemic Agreement (Accord) was agreed in principle at the WHO Intergovernmental Negotiating Body (INB) in April 2025 and adopted at the World Health Assembly in May 2025. It is now in the ratification phase in 2026. Civil society celebrated the deal as a 'first step' but criticized diluted provisions on intellectual property, technology transfer, and access to medical countermeasures.",
   whyNow:"The accord's effectiveness depends entirely on how ambiguous provisions on IP waivers, pathogen sharing (PABS system), and equitable access are interpreted in implementing regulations. Big Pharma lobbied hard to weaken the text; now civil society must push governments to implement strongly. WHA79 (May 2026) is the next major review.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"People's Medicines Alliance",url:"https://peoplesmedicines.org"},{name:"Médecins Sans Frontières — Access Campaign",url:"https://www.msf.org/access-medicines"},{name:"Oxfam Health",url:"https://www.oxfam.org/en/what-we-do/issues/health"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"WHA79 (May 2026) is the next major WHO governance moment. PABS implementing agreement negotiations are ongoing in 2026.",
   sources:[{title:"People's Medicines Alliance — WHO Agreement Reaction",url:"https://peoplesmedicines.org/resources/media-releases/who-pandemic-agreement-must-only-be-the-first-step/",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:8,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:43},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#PandemicTreaty","#PeoplesVaccine","#HealthEquity"],tags:["health-equity","pandemic-prep"]},

  {id:205,name:"Stop Killer Robots — Autonomous Weapons Treaty",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Disarmament / AI Ethics",
   description:"The Stop Killer Robots coalition (274+ organizations) is campaigning for a binding international treaty to ban fully autonomous weapons systems that can select and attack targets without human control. The UN General Assembly's First Committee adopted resolutions on autonomous weapons for three consecutive years. A growing bloc of states has signaled readiness to start treaty negotiations in 2026.",
   whyNow:"AI-driven autonomous targeting is being deployed in active conflicts (Gaza, Ukraine), making the issue viscerally urgent. A UNGA resolution in November 2025 showed growing state consensus. The UN Secretary-General has called these weapons 'morally repugnant.' 2026–2027 is the window for formal treaty mandate.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Stop Killer Robots",url:"https://stopkillerrobots.org"},{name:"Human Rights Watch — Arms",url:"https://www.hrw.org/topic/arms"},{name:"Amnesty International — Arms Control",url:"https://www.amnesty.org/en/what-we-do/arms-control/"},{name:"Article 36",url:"https://article36.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Conference on Disarmament (Jan–Mar 2026, Geneva), First Committee UNGA (Oct–Nov 2026). 2026 is the critical year for escalating from resolutions to formal treaty negotiations mandate.",
   sources:[{title:"Stop Killer Robots — News",url:"https://stopkillerrobots.org/news/",verified:true},{title:"Stop Killer Robots Homepage",url:"https://stopkillerrobots.org",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:7,conformity_trap_risk:4,benefit_visibility:8,penalty_reduction:9,broad_angle_potential:9,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:45},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑↑",
   slogans:["#StopKillerRobots","#BanKillerRobots","Keep a Human In The Loop"],tags:["ai-governance","military-tech"]},

  {id:206,name:"CSW70 — Women's Access to Justice",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Gender Equality / Women's Rights",
   description:"The 70th Session of the Commission on the Status of Women (CSW70), held March 9–19, 2026 at UN Headquarters, is the UN's largest annual gathering on gender equality. The priority theme is 'Ensuring and strengthening access to justice for all women and girls.' Over 10,000 delegates from government, civil society, and NGOs attend.",
   whyNow:"The session happens at a moment of sharp global backlash against gender rights — rollback of abortion rights, femicide crises in Latin America, rollback of LGBTQ+ protections. The 'access to justice' theme directly engages legal system reform and discriminatory laws. This is a prime moment for feminist activists to set the global agenda.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"UN Women",url:"https://www.unwomen.org"},{name:"DAWN",url:"https://dawnnet.org"},{name:"Feminist Green New Deal coalition",url:"https://feministgreennewdeal.com"},{name:"AWID",url:"https://www.awid.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"CSW70 Agreed Conclusions (adopted March 19, 2026) establish 5-year global policy benchmarks on women's access to justice. Key window to embed strong language on reproductive rights, GBV legal accountability.",
   sources:[{title:"UN Women — CSW70",url:"https://www.unwomen.org/en/how-we-work/commission-on-the-status-of-women/csw70-2026",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:6,conformity_trap_risk:5,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:8,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:41},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#CSW70","#FeministFuture","#WomensRights","#GenderJustice"],tags:["gender-equality","human-rights"]},

  {id:207,name:"UN Permanent Forum on Indigenous Issues (UNPFII 25)",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Indigenous Rights / Health",
   description:"The 25th Session of UNPFII meets April 20–May 1, 2026 at UN Headquarters with the theme 'Ensuring Indigenous Peoples' health, including in the context of conflict.' This brings together Indigenous delegates, member states, and UN agencies to address Indigenous health rights intersecting with armed conflict, climate displacement, and territorial dispossession.",
   whyNow:"Multiple ongoing crises intersect: Gaza conflict, Sudan, Myanmar, and Canada residential school health legacy. The theme explicitly connects health, conflict, and territorial rights. UNPFII recommendations carry formal status in UN system and can influence BBNJ, CBD, UNFCCC, and INC plastics processes.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"UN Permanent Forum on Indigenous Issues",url:"https://social.desa.un.org/issues/indigenous-peoples/unpfii"},{name:"International Indigenous Peoples Forum on Climate Change",url:"https://indigenousclimateportal.com"},{name:"Cultural Survival",url:"https://www.culturalsurvival.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"UNPFII 25 recommendations (May 2026) formally submitted to ECOSOC and UN agencies. These influence BBNJ PrepCom, CBD COP, and HLPF SDG reviews. FPIC operationalization is the key battleground.",
   sources:[{title:"UNPFII 25th Session — UN DESA",url:"https://social.desa.un.org/issues/indigenous-peoples/unpfii/25th-session",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:5,conformity_trap_risk:5,benefit_visibility:7,penalty_reduction:9,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:41},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#UNPFII25","#IndigenousRights","#FPIC","#NothingAboutUsWithoutUs"],tags:["indigenous-rights","health-equity"]},

  {id:208,name:"Global Digital Compact — AI Governance Implementation",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Digital Governance / AI",
   description:"The Global Digital Compact (GDC), adopted at the UN Summit of the Future (September 2024), is a comprehensive framework for digital cooperation and AI governance. 2026 is the first full year of GDC implementation, with civil society pushing for meaningful inclusion in AI governance forums, regulation of surveillance technologies, and bridging the digital divide.",
   whyNow:"The GDC's AI provisions are being operationalized exactly as generative AI's social impacts are peaking. The ITU's AI for Good Global Summit (July 7–10, 2026, Geneva) is a major convergence point. Civil society is fighting to prevent GDC from becoming a pro-industry document.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"UN Office for Digital and Emerging Technologies",url:"https://www.un.org/digital-emerging-technologies"},{name:"Association for Progressive Communications",url:"https://www.apc.org"},{name:"Access Now",url:"https://www.accessnow.org"},{name:"Algorithm Watch",url:"https://algorithmwatch.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"GDC implementation began January 2026. AI for Good Summit (July 2026) is first major accountability checkpoint. Internet Governance Forum 2026 will feature civil society GDC monitoring.",
   sources:[{title:"Global Digital Compact — UN",url:"https://www.un.org/digital-emerging-technologies/global-digital-compact",verified:true},{title:"AI for Good Summit 2026",url:"https://aiforgood.itu.int/summit26/",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:6,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:6,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:8,leader_persistence:6,overall_readiness:40},deployWindow:"watch",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#GlobalDigitalCompact","#AIGovernance","#DigitalJustice","#AIAccountability"],tags:["ai-governance","digital-rights"]},

  {id:209,name:"UNCCD COP17 — Land Degradation and Desertification",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Land Rights / Desertification",
   description:"The 17th Conference of the Parties to the UN Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD COP17) will be held in Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia, August 17–28, 2026. It focuses on land degradation, drought resilience, and desertification affecting over 3.2 billion people globally. This COP arrives as the UNCCD's Land Degradation Neutrality (LDN) targets approach the 2030 deadline.",
   whyNow:"Mongolia hosting shifts the spotlight to Central Asian nomadic communities and the devastating impact of dzud (extreme cold and snow events). Civil society pushing for recognition of land rights, pastoralist communities, and the connection between land degradation and forced migration.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"UNCCD Secretariat",url:"https://www.unccd.int"},{name:"International Land Coalition",url:"https://www.landcoalition.org"},{name:"World Agroforestry",url:"https://www.worldagroforestry.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"COP17 (Aug 2026) is the primary decision point for UNCCD drought protocol finalization, LDN progress review, and land rights commitments.",
   sources:[{title:"UNCCD Convention to Combat Desertification",url:"https://www.unccd.int",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:5,conformity_trap_risk:5,benefit_visibility:6,penalty_reduction:7,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:6,overall_readiness:36},deployWindow:"watch",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#UNCCDCOP17","#LandIsLife","#FightDesertification","#RestoreLand"],tags:["land-rights","climate-adaptation"]},

  {id:210,name:"HLPF 2026 — SDG Accountability (Water, Energy, Cities)",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Sustainable Development / SDGs",
   description:"The High-level Political Forum on Sustainable Development (HLPF 2026) meets July 6–15, 2026 at UN Headquarters. It will conduct in-depth reviews of SDGs 6 (water), 7 (energy), 9 (infrastructure), 11 (cities), and 17 (partnerships). 36 countries will present Voluntary National Reviews. With 4 years to the 2030 SDG deadline, this is a critical accountability moment.",
   whyNow:"The SDG midpoint (2023) showed the world drastically off track — only 17% of SDG targets are on course. HLPF 2026 is the major follow-up accountability moment specifically for water, energy, and cities — three SDGs critical to climate adaptation and urban equity.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"UN DESA HLPF Secretariat",url:"https://hlpf.un.org/2026"},{name:"SDG Action Campaign",url:"https://www.sdgactioncampaign.org"},{name:"Global Policy Forum",url:"https://www.globalpolicy.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"HLPF 2026 Ministerial Declaration (July 15, 2026) and country VNRs create accountability benchmarks.",
   sources:[{title:"HLPF 2026 — Official",url:"https://hlpf.un.org/2026",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:5,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:6,penalty_reduction:6,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:5,overall_readiness:36},deployWindow:"watch",trajectory:"→",
   slogans:["#HLPF2026","#SDGs2030","#LeaveNoOneBehind","#WaterForAll"],tags:["sdgs","development"]},

  {id:211,name:"Universal Periodic Review (UPR) — Human Rights Accountability",region:"Global",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Human Rights",
   description:"The Universal Periodic Review (UPR) is the UN mechanism reviewing every country's human rights record in rotating cycles. In 2026, three sessions (January, May, November) will review 42 countries including Australia, France, Germany, and Saudi Arabia. Civil society organizations submit 'stakeholder reports' that directly influence state recommendations.",
   whyNow:"With global human rights backsliding — from LGBTQ+ rights rollbacks to crackdowns on environmental defenders — UPR 2026 provides concrete leverage mechanisms. Australia under review in January 2026 (as it holds COP31 presidency) creates a unique accountability moment.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"UPR Info NGO",url:"https://upr-info.org"},{name:"Amnesty International",url:"https://www.amnesty.org"},{name:"Human Rights Watch",url:"https://www.hrw.org"},{name:"CIVICUS",url:"https://civicus.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"UPR stakeholder submissions due 6-8 months before each session. January 2026 session (Australia under review): leverage moment given COP31 presidency.",
   sources:[{title:"UPR Info — States Under Review",url:"https://upr-info.org",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:4,conformity_trap_risk:6,benefit_visibility:5,penalty_reduction:8,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:6,overall_readiness:36},deployWindow:"watch",trajectory:"→",
   slogans:["#UPR2026","#HumanRightsReview","#HoldGovernmentsAccountable"],tags:["human-rights","accountability"]},

  // ===== CANADA CASES 2026 (IDs 250-260) =====

  {id:250,name:"Alberta Sovereignty & Separation Movement",region:"Canada — Alberta",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Provincial Sovereignty / Separatism",
   description:"The Alberta Prosperity Project (APP), a far-right separatist group, is collecting signatures under Danielle Smith's Citizen Initiative Act to trigger a fall 2026 referendum on Alberta leaving Canada. With a May 2 deadline to gather 177,732 valid signatures, the APP faces challenges. A competing 'Forever Canadian' petition gathered 456,365 signatures in 2025.",
   whyNow:"The APP referendum push has a hard May 2026 deadline. The Carney-led Liberal federal government is viewed by many conservative Albertans as antithetical to Alberta's oil interests. A provincial election looms in 2027, making 2026 the critical inflection year.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Alberta Prosperity Project",url:"https://www.albertaprosperityproject.ca"},{name:"Take Back Alberta",url:"https://www.takebackalberta.ca"},{name:"rabble.ca (coverage)",url:"https://rabble.ca/politics/canadian-politics/is-the-alberta-prosperity-project-having-trouble-getting-signatures-for-separation-petition/"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"May 2, 2026 signature deadline under Citizen Initiative Act; constitutional courts will likely be involved. Provincial election 2027.",
   sources:[{title:"rabble.ca — APP Signature Troubles",url:"https://rabble.ca/politics/canadian-politics/is-the-alberta-prosperity-project-having-trouble-getting-signatures-for-separation-petition/",verified:true},{title:"The Tyee — Preston Manning vs APP",url:"https://thetyee.ca/News/2026/03/02/Preston-Manning-Claps-Back-Alberta-Secession-Leader/",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:5,conformity_trap_risk:7,benefit_visibility:6,penalty_reduction:4,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:8,overall_readiness:37},deployWindow:"act-now",trajectory:"→",
   slogans:["#AlbertaFirst","#FreeAlberta"],tags:["separatism","canadian-politics"]},

  {id:251,name:"Quebec Sovereignty Renaissance — Millennial Wave",region:"Canada — Quebec",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Provincial Sovereignty / Cultural Independence",
   description:"A generational shift is underway in Quebec's independence movement. The Parti Québécois, polling ahead heading into the next provincial election, has revived referendum promises. A new Montreal café 'Club Pays' opened in March 2026 specifically as a hub for millennial and Gen Z sovereigntists, inspired by Catalonian independence cafés.",
   whyNow:"PQ leads provincial polls ahead of 2026-2027 election. Canada's pivot toward national unity in the face of US tariffs has created both pressure on and against sovereigntism. The Catalonian cultural organizing model is being directly transplanted to Montreal.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"OUI Québec",url:"https://ouiquebec.qc.ca"},{name:"Parti Québécois",url:"https://pq.org"},{name:"Mouvement national des Québécoises et Québécois",url:"https://www.mnq.quebec"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"Provincial election cycle (expected 2026-2027). A PQ majority would trigger legislative planning for a third referendum.",
   sources:[{title:"CBC — Club Pays café opens",url:"https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/oui-quebec-cafe-pays-9.7129150",verified:true}],
   ncrs:{tipping_threshold:4,conformity_trap_risk:8,benefit_visibility:5,penalty_reduction:5,broad_angle_potential:7,leader_persistence:7,overall_readiness:36},deployWindow:"prepare",trajectory:"↑",
   slogans:["#Indépendance","#OuiQuébec","Un pays, c'est une joie collective"],tags:["separatism","canadian-politics"]},

  {id:252,name:"Canada-US Trade War — Buy Canadian Movement",region:"Canada — National",year:2026,failed:false,
   issue:"Economic Sovereignty / Anti-Tariff",
   description:"Donald Trump's imposition of broad tariffs on Canadian goods in 2025 triggered a surge of Canadian economic nationalism. 'Buy Canadian' campaigns swept social media and consumer behavior shifted measurably away from American products. The federal government under Mark Carney deployed retaliatory tariffs. Quebec SAQ began removing US liquor.",
   whyNow:"As of March 2026, the tariff war is still active. Carney's minority Liberal government is defined partly by this conflict. Oil prices soaring post-Iran conflict create Alberta/Ottawa tensions while also giving Canada leverage. CUSMA/USMCA renegotiation window in late 2026.",
   keyOrgs:[{name:"Council of Canadians",url:"https://canadians.org"},{name:"Canadian Labour Congress",url:"https://clc-ctc.ca"},{name:"Unifor",url:"https://www.unifor.org"}],
   regulatoryWindow:"CUSMA/USMCA review deadline late 2026. Federal budget 2026 allocating funds for trade diversification.",
